mod1 <- lm(score ~ bty,
           data = d)
get_regression_table(mod1)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 7
  term      estimate std_error statistic p_value lower_ci upper_ci
  <chr>        <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>   <dbl>    <dbl>    <dbl>
1 intercept    3.88      0.076     51.0        0    3.73     4.03 
2 bty          0.067     0.016      4.09       0    0.035    0.099

Intercept = 3.88

Slope = .067

For every +1 in beauty score, we expect the teaching evaluation to go up .067.

mod1preds <- get_regression_points(mod1)

head(mod1preds)
# A tibble: 6 Ã 5
     ID score   bty score_hat residual
  <int> <dbl> <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
1     1   4.7     5      4.21    0.486
2     2   4.1     5      4.21   -0.114
3     3   3.9     5      4.21   -0.314
4     4   4.8     5      4.21    0.586
5     5   4.6     3      4.08    0.52 
6     6   4.3     3      4.08    0.22

A residual is the leftover. For instance, we have prof 1 have a bty score of 5 and an evaluation score of 4.7. According to our slope and y-intercept values, this professor should get a score of 4.214, which we see under the score_hat column. However, this professor got a 4.7, and score 0.486 points higher than the expected score, which we see under the residual column.
